29. adesdum. In later Latin this enclitic use of dum is confined to the negatives nondum, nedum, vixdum, to dudum and interdum, and the imperatives agedum, agitedum. It is used by the comic poets with all imperatives (eg. abidum Haut. 249, circumspicedum Plaut.Trin. 146), with ebo (184, 616). Quidum (interrogative) is found in Terence, e. g. Hee. 319, primumdum Plaut. Trin. 98. WVhether adesdum, etc. should be written in one word or two is an unimportant point, on which no agreement seems to have been made.

servibas, Terence and Plautus seem to have used -ibam or -z'ebam for the imperfect of the fourth conjugation almost at pleasure‚ e.g. 930 aicbat, 932 aibat, and Phorm. 83 serviebam but always scibam, nescibam. The shorter form is sometimes employed by later poets, e. g. accibant, by Lucretius; audibant. custodibant, by Catullus; lenibat, nutribant, vestibat, by Vergil; audibat, mollibat. by Ovid; largibar, by Propertius.
